Lieutenant Paul Vance, Connecticut police spokesman, said the force was in discussion with federal authorities over aggressively tracking down and prosecuting anyone who commits violations in this way.</p><p>Vance said there had been cases of people posing on Facebook as the shooter, of misinformation being circulated on websites and of threatening behaviour. &quot;These issues are crimes and they will be investigated stateside and federally, and prosecutions will take place when people are identified,&quot; he said.</p><p>A dramatic illustration of the insidious actions of hoaxers was provided on Sunday morning at the St Rose of Lima church, where local people had gathered to mourn the dead. Worshippers hurriedly left the building after someone phoned in a threat, though police later said nothing dangerous had been found.</p><p>The threat interrupted a busy mass, sent worshippers rushing from the church and touched off a large police response two days after the worst massacre of school-age children in US history. Anna Wood of Oxford, Connecticut, one of the worshippers who left the church, said that halfway through the noon service the priest stopped and said: &quot;Please, everybody leave. There is a threat.&quot;</p><p>The police forensic investigation has almost been completed on the outside of the school, and vehicles parked there are being released to their owners. But the search inside the school is likely to take several more days, police have indicated.</p><p>Investigators are also continuing to look into the guns that were used at the school. Vance said that four guns that the gunman had on his possession at the time of the killings were being traced back to their origins. It has been reported that the guns belonged to Nancy Lanza, though that has not been confirmed publicly by police.</p><p>The immediate futures of the almost 700 students at Sandy Hook school, who range in age from five to 10, is in doubt. The school is likely to remain closed for weeks if not months, and there is debate about whether it should ever reopen.</p><p>Lieutenant George Sinko of Connecticut police said that &quot;at this time I would find it very difficult&quot; to return children to the building, but added that the matter was &quot;being looked into&quot;. He said: &quot;We want to keep these kids together â€“ they need the support of each other.&quot;</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/401173572|2012-12-22T11:49:04Z|3e50437896b0f7d71974d21993bf5075f8abb619 -->","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2012-12-16T20:43:50Z","hasStoryPackage":"true","score":"1.0","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/12/16/1355690141473/Mourners-looks-at-the-nam-005.jpg","standfirst":"Bodies of children killed at Sandy Hook elementary school returned to parents as police warn over social media misuse","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3chgx","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/12/16/1355690141473/Mourners-looks-at-the-nam-005.jpg","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"401173572","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Ed Pilkington and Adam Gabbatt in Newtown","publication":"guardian.co.uk","internalPageCode":"1843345","shouldHideAdverts":"true","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-12-19T20:43:50Z"},"tags":[{"id":"world/newtown-shooting","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webTitle":"Newtown shooting","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/newtown-shooting","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/newtown-shooting","references":[]},{"id":"world/gun-crime","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webTitle":"Gun crime","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/gun-crime","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/gun-crime","references":[]},{"id":"world/us-crime","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webTitle":"US crime","webUrl":"http://www.gu